<subsection xml:id="subsec-solving-linear-simultaneous-equations-using-graphs">
    <title>Solving linear simultaneous equations using graphs</title>
    <p>
        Linear simultaneous equations are algebraic equations with the same variables and are solved at the same time.
    </p>
    <p>
        One of the ways of solving simultaneous equations is graphical method.
    </p>
    <p>
        Here is an activity on how to solve simultaneous equations graphically.
    </p>
    <activity>
    <statement>
         <p>
            Solve the following simultaneous equations graphically: 
        </p>
        <p>
            <me>
                y = -x + 4
            </me>  
            <me>
                y = 2x +1 
            </me> 
        </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
        <p>
            Make separate tables of <m>x \text{ and } y</m> variables for each equation.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="equations">
            <caption>Simultaneous_equations</caption>
            <sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
               <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell><m> y = -x + 4 </m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <tabular>
                <row>
                    <cell><m> y = 2x +1 </m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular> 
            </sidebyside>   
        </figure>
        <figure xml:id="tables">
            <caption>Tables</caption>
            <sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
            <tabular valign="top" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor"> 
                <row halign="center">
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                </row>

                <row halign="center">
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>

            <tabular valign="top" top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" right="minor"> 
                <row halign="center">
                    <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                </row>

                <row halign="center">
                    <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
                
            </sidebyside>
        </figure>
        
        <p>
            Construct the two lines for the equations in your graph as shown below.
        </p>
        <figure>
            <caption>Graph</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="geogebra-linear-graph1" platform="geogebra" width="90%" aspect="4:3">
            <slate xml:id="linear-graph1" surface="geogebra" material="ahrrtrmg" aspect="4:3">
                enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                showResetIcon(false);
            </slate>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
        <p>
            Identiffy the point of intersection of the two lines, that is point <m>(1,3)</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            The solution for the two simultaneous equations is the coordinates of the intersection of the two lines. <m>x = 1</m> and <m>y = 3.</m>
        </p>    
    </solution>   
    </activity>
    
</subsection>